<span id="freeTextContainer16254766461134085436">So much fun!<br/><br/>Not one of my absolute favorites (I tend to be more of a Poirot fan) but very satisfying. And it&apos;s one of the better Miss Marple ones--I enjoyed her fighting to remain a person and not simply one of the elderly!<br/><br/>Marina Gregg is a famous but faded film star known for her beauty, performances, and nervous breakdowns. Having purchased a home in Miss Marple&apos;s village of St. Mary&apos;s Mead, she and her husband, director Jason Rudd throw a big party to which the entire town is invited. At a sp</span>
  <span id="freeText16254766461134085436" style="display:none">So much fun!<br /><br />Not one of my absolute favorites (I tend to be more of a Poirot fan) but very satisfying. And it's one of the better Miss Marple ones--I enjoyed her fighting to remain a person and not simply one of the elderly!<br /><br />Marina Gregg is a famous but faded film star known for her beauty, performances, and nervous breakdowns. Having purchased a home in Miss Marple's village of St. Mary's Mead, she and her husband, director Jason Rudd throw a big party to which the entire town is invited. At a special reception upstairs, Marina greets guests, one of whom dies shortly after their meeting.<br /><br />No more information: spoilers slip in too easily, especially when I'm talking about a book I've read several times. The reason for 4 stars instead of 5 is that I guessed the murderer's identity early on which I hate. However, despite that, I loved the characters and their interactions as well as the various puzzles that emerge along the way and the variety of motives for murdering the film star.<br /><br />I recently saw the film version of the book, with one of those "star-studded" casts, including Elizabeth Taylor as Marina and Rock Hudson as her husband. Angela Lansbury is not my idea of Jane Marple (see Joan Hickson's work) but she is always delightful to watch. Not a perfect adaptation but fun nonetheless.</span>
